sellerComment: If you are looking for an inconspicuous car with a great ride and excellent snow and ice handling you are undoubtedly in the wrong place. If comfort, space and reliability are high on your list of demands you need to stop looking at Jeeps in general and Wranglers specifically.However, if you want an adult toy that has been lovingly crafted to allow you to drive 4 hours to Tahoma (in relative comfort) and then head down its namesake then this is the rig for you. Pretty much ever modification to this Jeep has been done with a focus on function without entirely compromising its use as a daily driver.'But wait!' you say, 'If this Jeep is as awesome as you say then why would you sell it?' - 'Good question strawman I just invented'. Last July I got knocked off my Harley by an inattentive kid and lost the last 18 inches of my right leg. After no little practice I have been forced to the heartbreaking conclusion that manual transmissions are not terribly safe in my condition. sellerComment: I m selling my baby because of a baby.  While a trail-rated, six-speed, two-door, soft-top Jeep is awesome for dirt roads, snow, and summer drives with the top down, it is not great for child seats, infants, or wives who find it hard to shift and waive a rattle around.  So, the new kid is in, and my Wrangler is out.I bought this Jeep new in 2007.  I actually ordered it from the factory while I was deployed with the U.S. Army in 2006.  I had dreams of lifting it, slapping on some big, bad tires, and taking it off road.  As you can see from the photos, that never happened.  It s pretty much still stock, and it has rarely felt anything but pavement.  It has an after-market Pioneer stereo (iPhone hookup and Bluetooth) to go with the factory-upgraded Infinity speakers and subwoofer.  Clean CARFAX.I did your comparison shopping for you (but you should still do your own research), and here s what I found: Jeeps like this list around $12,900.  Those Jeeps have better wheels and newer tops.  They typically have higher miles, and they don t have the upgraded speakers.  Wear and tear is similar.  My Jeep has a golf ball size dent in the passenger door, and I ve worn out the steering wheel and floor.  Apparently, I ve put my hand and heel in the same spots everyday for the last ten years.  You can t Jeep Waive from anywhere else, though.  (If you re not going to Jeep Waive, don t call.)  There s a red one in Colorado Springs for $10,500 with 116,000 miles and a hard top.  There might be something wrong with it, but if there isn t, that s a great deal, and you should go buy that one!  If you miss it, though, give me a call.If you re curious, I now have a Volvo.

Speaking of Jeep dealerships, I believe the 5 year or 100,000 mile Powertrain/Roadside Assistance Limited Warranty goes with the vehicle (possible transfer fee). Bonus: This was the last year of the 100,000 Mile Warranty. Since the Jeep was first registered on 07-28-15, there may be several months left on the 3 year or 36K mile Basic Limited Warranty. Seems logical but I can't guarantee it. The reason I'm letting this great Jeep Wrangler go is because from day one my older Collie couldn't jump up in the back. sellerComment: Say hello to my Jeep Wrangler arctic edition. If you have a real need for all-season capability, 4-Doors, or simply a strong desire to depart the beaten path, my 2012 Jeep Wrangler is a tough recipe to beat. I've maintained her well and only put 52K miles on her in 6 years, she's basically a new car, never had an accident and never broken down. Under the hood sits a powerful 3.6 liter V6 that produces 285 horsepower and almost as much torque. Combined with the rock-solid Dana front and rear axles, this 5-Speed automatic transmission will allow you to maintain civility or allow you to carve your own path where ever you see fit thanks to the locking differentials, Rock-Trac HD transfer case, and gas charged. This jeep goes beyond basic by offering Air Conditioning, 4 wheel drive, power windows/locks, and special badging. With city streets and freeways providing an increasingly unfriendly atmosphere to standard, car-based suspension and real ground clearance are increasingly handy for the committed urbanite. If you get the urge to take an open-air cruise, just remove the top, put on some shades, crank up the Infinity sound system, and hit the road! A strong safety cage surrounds you, multi stage airbags protect you, and Hill-start and stability control help you along the way. My arctic offers all of the legendary rock-climbing ability of America's favorite off-roader, with a dose of comfort to go along for the ride!-This is $3K below market value-She's been meticulously detailed-No off roading, ever -Inspected and given a full fluid refresh and certification by dealership of perfect mechanical conditionWhy I am selling her: I moved to Seattle from Texas in 2014 and rarely ever drive her, hence why she has 52K miles in just 6 years. I work from home and Seattle is a smaller city that I can easily navigate on foot, she sits in the garage and is useful when I have family in town a few times a year.

sellerComment: This Jeep has been a restoration project, but my priorities have changed and now needs to go to someone else.First things:- Clear title in hand.- Frame is in fantastic shape; practically no rust - it's why I bought it in the first place.Things done to it:- Engine completely and professionally rebuilt. You can consider it new. Less than 100 miles on it. Currently has break-in oil in it.- Transmission recently professionally rebuilt and sealed with new synchronizers.- New (all five) oversize tires. 31X10.50R15 - custom wheels in perfect shape.- New suspension/springs/shocks/bushings all around. Steering aligned; no death wobble.- HEI distributor installed. New oil pump.- New brakes all around; new front rotors, new rear drums. New brake fluid.- New clutch, new clutch fluid.- New ball-joints, new front hubs/joints. New axle seals.- New differential oil.- New no-weld exhaust.- New gas tank/fuel pump/fuel lines/tank fill sensor.- Sport seats installed with 4-point seat belts.- It runs great. The carb is an aftermarket Weber 32/36 DGAV33B1.Things that are meh:- The carb was rebuilt, but could probably stand some fine-tuning. The HEI distributor doesn't like the vacuum advance, so that's disabled. A local carb shop tells me this is normal.- There is a 3-inch body lift on it, which messes a bit with the alignment of certain things which can be pointed out when we talk. Everything is fully functional though.- The soft-top could be better, but it works fine.Things that need work:- The middle dash is non-existent. I'm working on replacing it, but you might do better if you're into that sort of thing. I have a gauge cover, but not the cluster.I put a lot of effort into making things right with this Jeep. Prior work that was poor has been fixed and/or replaced.

carFeaturesText: CD PlayerCruise Control
sellerComment: I have a very clean 2006 Jeep Wrangler LJ.  6 speed transmission, Black hard top with black spiderweb shade for the nice weather driving.  Silver in color with dark charcoal interior.  The Jeep just had a new oil pan gasket installed by the dealership I bought it from.  Also had new tires put on it 4,000 miles ago.  I installed new spark plugs within the last 1,000 miles as well and changed the transmission fluid with full synthetic.  Jeep also has a new battery and magnaflow exhaust.    Has large aftermarket LED lights up on the bumper.  I believe the fender flares are aftermarket (they are wider than normal) but other than that, the Jeep is stock.  Doors are full doors.  Jeep has the stock stereo, cruise control, and heat/AC work great.   I have never taken this Jeep off the pavement.The Jeep drives great!  It s a blast to drive.  Changes in the family and the purchase of a new pickup truck have forced the sale.  I will definitely miss it.  The bad - while clay barring and waxing the Jeep I found some rust in the front left fender where dirt and crud had embedded between the actual fender and the fender flare and created an issue.  I removed the fender flare, removed the rust (good sheet metal under the rust), and applied POR-15.  This spot was about the size of a quarter and was not through the metal.  This Jeep is not a  rust bucket  but I am trying to disclose everything.  On cold startup it has the  Jeep tick  that goes away as it warms up.  I asked online and was told this is fairly common and just part of owning a Jeep, but I am disclosing it as I am not a mechanic and when I asked, people told me it s just a Jeep thing.  When the motor is cold it has a tick noise, as it warms it goes away.  Again, from what I was told this is quite common.  This is a VERY CLEAN Jeep.  These Unlimited long wheelbase models are becoming more and more difficult to find, especially this clean.  Drives straight, unmolested, and clean!!!!
